                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee/632: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-12T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 12, 1933—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>373. Your 736, October 11, midnight. I quite agree with you that so long as a
                    possibility exists of persuading Germany to “negotiate” <pb facs="0355" n="253"
                        xml:id="pg_253"/> a suitable treaty which maintains the essence of our
                    present position unimpaired but which is so phrased as to meet her
                    susceptibilities, we should continue our endeavors to do so. To this end I
                    gladly approve your pursuing the course of action you recommend. I suggest,
                    however, that you exercise especial care not to let the Germans feel that (<hi
                        rend="italic">a</hi>) we are weakening on a question of principle or (<hi
                        rend="italic">b</hi>) that a difference of opinion which they can exploit
                    exists between ourselves on the one hand and the British and French on the
                    other.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
